article.headline: Mercury, without Taurasi, wins fourth straight
article.linkText: Shiny Penny: Taylor scores 31 to lead Mercury
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Penny Taylor more than made up for Diana
Taurasi's absence.

Taylor had the best offensive night by a Mercury player this
season. scoring a season-high 31 points and adding seven rebounds
and seven assists to help the Mercury beat the Washington Mystics
77-66 Friday night.

"Obviously with Diana out, we had some big shoes to fill,"
Taylor said. "A little nervous without our point guard and our
leader. I just came out and tried to give a little extra and I
think that was the key for everyone on the floor -- just giving that
little bit extra to make up for Diana's offense, defense and her
leadership on the floor."

Taurasi, the 2004 rookie of the year who is fifth in the league
in scoring at 16.8 points per game, missed a game for the first
time in her career due to a bruised right knee she injured in
Wednesday's win over Charlotte. Phoenix coach Carrie Graf described
her as "day-to-day."

Alana Beard scored 16 points and DeLisha Milton-Jones added 15
for the Mystics (9-9), losers of two of their last three after
winning five of their previous six.

"We had no answer for Penny Taylor," Washington coach Richie
Adubato said. "We also had no answer for Maria Stepanova. She had
three blocks and scored some baskets that really gave them momentum
while we were trying to make a comeback."

Stepanova had 17 points and seven rebounds and Anna DeForge
added 16 for Phoenix (7-11), which lost five straight before its
current winning streak.

"Our ability to handle adversity -- obviously we didn't have
Taurasi and Shereka Wright's wrist was not fresh -- to come away
with that win was huge," Graf said.

Taylor, who was 5-of-8 from beyond the 3-point line, started a
key 7-0 run after Washington had tied the game at 55 with 9:37 left
in the game.

Taylor stole the ball, and was headed for a layup when she was
flagrantly fouled by Beard. After making the two free throws,
Taylor hit her sixth 3-pointer of the night and Phoenix held off
Washington for the win. The Mystics never got closer than three.

"Sometimes you just have those nights," Taylor said. "In the
shootaround today, my shot felt good and I thought I'll take a
couple and once you get on a roll you stick with it."

The Mercury made 12 of their first 17 shots, and opened up a
30-15 lead in the first 10 minutes and led 45-34 at halftime.
Taylor had 17 points and six assists at the break, including 4-of-5
from outside the 3-point arc.

Phoenix, the worst shooting team in the league at 39 percent,
shot over 50 percent for the second night in a row, making 27 of 51
field goals (53 percent).

"When you get wins, it builds momentum, it builds confidence
and they're enjoying it right now and understanding how we need to
play to win," Graf said.
